2. Process Safety Information ? Process safety information is maintained for each operating area (FSG 1.30 Process Safety File Management System outlines this process);
3. Process Hazard Analysis ? A detailed hazard assessment, using the HAZOP and WHAT-if/Checklist methodologies, is conducted on all processes to insure that they have been designed safely.  The process also includes a Layer of Protection analysis; 
4. Operating Procedures ? A system is in place to ensure that updated and approved procedures cover all aspects of process unit operation;
5. Training ? A training program has been established to ensure that all personnel are well trained in the specific duties of their jobs (The process also includes an annual Training Needs Analysis);
6. Contractors ? It is Cedar Bayou?s objective to partner with contractors that share the same safety philosophy.  A dedicated, collective, and consistent approach by Cedar Bayou and contractors will enhance and maintain the safety and health of our respective employees FSG 7.10 (Contractor Plant Safety Procedures) outlines this process;
7. Prestartup Safety Review ? A prestartup safety review walk down and checklist is completed for each managed change that significantly impacts the Process Safety Information.  FSG 4.75 (Formal Facility/Equipment Acceptance Procedure) outline this process; 
8. Mechanical Integrity ? An equipment inspection program is in place to ensure equipment remains in good condition to prevent releases;
9. Hot Work Permits ? A work permit system is in place to ensure that all work on process equipment and all hot work are conducted in a safe manner.  F&SG 4.18 (Safe Work and Hot Work Permit Procedure) outlines this process;
10. Management of Change ? A management of change system has been established and implemented to ensure that any change is thoroughly reviewed prior to implementation.  FSG 4.02 (Management of Change) outlines this pro

cess; 
11. Incident Investigation ? Incidents are investigated using one of several industry recognized methodologies, such as Why Tree, to determine system level root causes that can be remedied to prevent a reoccurrence. Employees and contractors involved in the incident are included on the investigation team.  F&SG 3.12 (Incident Investigations) outlines this process; 
12. Emergency Planning and Response ? An emergency action plan has been established for the entire plant including procedures for handling small releases of chemicals.  The plan is known as the Integrated Contingency Plan;  
13. Compliance Audits ? Programs are audited annually through the VPP self assessment; at least every three years through PSM compliance audits; every three years through an internal corporate sponsored Operational Excellence/Compliance Review; and weekly safety inspections of the facility are conducted by  cross functional teams.  Action items resulting from these are tracked to a timely completion; 
14. Trade Secrets ? Access by employees to information has few restrictions. Contractor?s access to information is managed based on their involvement in PSM and the day to day activities of the plant. 

The Cedar Bayou plant became an OSHA STAR worksite in the Voluntary Protection Program (VPP) in 1997. The site was recertified to STAR status by OSHA in 2000 and 2004.  This voluntary program is a partnership between OSHA and industry to recognize and encourage excellence and continuous improvement in safety programs.  STAR certification represents the highest form of recognition OSHA can give a company for outstanding safety performance.

